LESSION 3 - DEPENDENCY INJECTION AND AUTOWIRING


Important Dependencies for spring applications
----------------------------------------------

Spring Web      -   for web applications
ThymeLeaf       -   for frontend development
Spring JPA      -   for connecting to DB
Actuator        -   for debugging purpose



compilation process
------------------

.java   -> .class file. if we compile .java file, then jvm turn it into .class file which is byte code.

core java   -> JAR file, if we compile core java file, then it packages it to JAR file.

Adv Java (web app)  -> WAR file, it we compile a spring app or any web app, it packages it to WAR file.




Annotations
------------

Spring specific annotations : 

    * spring core annotations :

                        1) @Component
                        2) @Service
                        3) @Repository
                        4) @Controller

    * Dependency Injections specific annotations :

                        1) @AutoWired
                        2) @Qualifier
                        3) @Primary
                        4) @Lazy
                        5) @PostConstruct
                        6) @PreDestroy
                        7) @Value


Springboot specific annotations : 


    * @SpringBootApplication, it include some annotation that are
        
                        1) @SpringBootConfiguration -> in spring, it is @Configurationn
                        2) @EnableAutoConfiguration
                        3) @ComponentScan

    * some conditional annotations

    * REST & WEB annotations

                        1) @Controller
                        2) @RestController
                        3) @RequestMapping
                        4) @GetMapping
                        5) @PostMapping
                        6) @PutMapping
                        7) @DeleteMapping
                        8) @PathVariable
                        9) @RequestParam
                       10) @RequestBody
                       11) @ResponseBody

    * some JPA annotations

                        1) @Repository
                        2) @Table
                        3) @column
                        4) @Entity
                        5) @Id
                        6) @Transactional
                        7) @GeneratedValue


    * Actuator annotations

                        1) @EndPoint
                        2) @ReadOperation
                        3) @WriteOperation
                        4) @DeleteOperation



BEAN SCOPES
-----------

Bean scopes defines how long a bean(object) can live and how many instances spring creates.

SCOPE = life cycle + visibility of a bean


scopes : 
--------

* Singleton (default) - one instance per spring container. same object shared everywhere.

* Prototype           - new instance every time you request the bean.

* request             - one instance per http request.

* session             - one instance per http session.

* application         - one instance per servletcontext.

* websocket           - one instance per websocket session.




Q) what does springapplication.run ?

    it sets up default configuration. starts spring application context automatically. starts/stops tomcat server. it scans class path.


AutoWiring
----------

* used to inject one class object into another class.


Q) diff b/w AutoWired and Qualifier ?

    * autowired search by type. if there are multiple instance are there. so it will look for its type.
    * qualifier search by name. if there are multiple types. it will look into that.



